Allows Next.js using Webpack 5 to work

There are a bunch of Webpack/Next.js issues to work around:

- `import.meta.url` generates `file:` URL. Using the `new URL` pattern
  tells Webpack to do runtime URLs.
- `experimental.asyncWebAssembly` causes Webpack to parse the wasm file
  and validate imports which it doesn't do correctly. Instead you need
  to use `type: "asset/resource"`.
  - But this puts the wasm file in `_next` which cause 404. We need to
    tell webpack to put the file in `static/` too

ScanIterator: Get rid of stream controller (#238)

At this point and for the foreseeable future, the actual iteration is
synchronous so enqueueing using a ReadableStreamDefaultController is
overkill (it will just put all the entries in an internal list).

We might want to allow some other way of iterating over the scan result
that allows early exits but that requires a change in the API so we can
deal with that later.

Follow up to #235

Call subscribe onData when query retval changes

For `subscribe`, we now only call `onData` if the return value of the
`body` function changes compared to last time.

This requires that we store the last return value to be able to compare
with that.

We consider the values equal if they behave like `JSON.stringify(a) ===
JSON.stringify(b)` except for the ordering of the property keys.

*BREAKING CHANGE*

This is a breaking API change because subscribe now has a slightly more
restricted type which can lead to new TypeScript type errors.

Also, we changed the type signature from `ToJSON` to `JSONValue` in a
few places.

Introduce a ConnectionLoop class with a delegate (#307)

This adds a new class, `ConnectionLoop` which is basically a run/game/dispatch loop. It runs forever but it is an async loop so it waits for state changes to continue.

It is factored in such a way that it can be used for both pull and push.

This has pretty extensive tests using fake timers which "easily" allows us to ensure we wait for 60s after a lot of failures etc.

Feat: Add scan().entries().toArray() etc (#353)

This adds convenience methods to the async iterator returned by scan, allowing
you to asynchronously get an array. For example:

```js
await scan().entries().toArray()
await scan().values().toArray()
await scan().keys().toArray()
await scan().toArray() // Same as values
```

keys can affect the subscription body we run it again and gather the used keys
again.
